{
  "nodes": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "label": "Linear Algebra",
      "color": "#667eea",
      "description": "This is the study of linear maps. These abstract objects form the natural language of quantum mechanics so it is essential for all aspiring physicists to learn this",
      "resources": {
        "Axler's Linear Algebra Done Right": "https://www.amazon.com/Linear-Algebra-Done-Right-Undergraduate/dp/0387982590",
        "Strang's Linear Algebra Lectures": "https://ocw.mit.edu/courses/18-06-linear-algebra-spring-2010/video_galleries/video-lectures/"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "label": "Calculus",
      "color": "#764ba2",
      "description": "Calculus is all about how things with change with time so it is a crucial tool.",
      "resources": {"Khan Academy Calculus 1": "https://www.khanacademy.org/math/calculus-1", "Khan Academy Calculus 2": "https://www.khanacademy.org/math/calculus-2", "Mathematical Methods for Physics and Engineering": "https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/mathematical-methods-for-physics-and-engineering/911A43AE1CF224743D32707FCC4AE0EB"}
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "label": "Classical Mechanics",
      "color": "#28a745",
      "description": "You may have studied mechanics in school using the idea of forces. It turns out there are different ways to formulate mechanics using Lagranians and Hamiltonians",
      "resources": {"The Theoretical Minimum: Classical Mechanics": "https://theoreticalminimum.com/courses/classical-mechanics/2011/fall", "David Tong's Notes": "https://www.damtp.cam.ac.uk/user/tong/dynamics.html"}
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "label": "Quantum Mechanics for Finite Systems",
      "color": "#007bff",
      "description": "Quantum mechanics is hard. But I think it's best learnt by starting with simple systems like those that are used in quantum computing.",
      "resources": {"Quantum Computation and Quantum Information": "https://www.amazon.co.uk/Quantum-Computation-Information-10th-Anniversary/dp/1107002176"}
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "label": "Quantum Mechanics for Continuous Systems",
      "color": "#17a2b8",
      "description": "With a better grasp of Classical Mechanics and finite dimensional quantum mechanics now you can study the quantum mechanics of particles.",
      "resources": {"Introduction to Quantum Mechanics": "https://www.amazon.co.uk/Introduction-Quantum-Mechanics-David-Griffiths/dp/1107189632", "David Tong's Notes": "https://www.damtp.cam.ac.uk/user/tong/quantum.html"}
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "label": "Group Theory",
      "color": "#ff6b6b",
      "description": "Symmetries play a major role in physics and group theory gives us the tools to describe them",
      "resources": {"Visual Group Theory": "https://www.amazon.co.uk/Visual-Group-Theory-Problem-Book/dp/088385757X"}
    },
    {
      "id": 7,
      "label": "Differential Geometry",
      "color": "#f093fb",
      "description": "This is using the tools from calculus to try understand shapes",
      "resources": {"Introduction to Smooth Manifolds": "https://www.amazon.co.uk/Introduction-Smooth-Manifolds-Graduate-Mathematics/dp/1489994750", "Introduction to Geometry and Topology": "https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-3-0348-0983-2", "Manifolds, Vector Fields, and Differential Forms": "https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-3-031-25409-3"}
    },
    {
      "id": 8,
      "label": "Classical Field Theory",
      "color": "#ffa500",
      "description": "We don't just want to understand particles, we would like to understand fields like the electromagenetic field",
      "resources": {"Classical Dynamics of Particles and Systems": "https://www.amazon.co.uk/Classical-Dynamics-Particles-Systems-Thornton/dp/0534408966", "Classical Mechanics (especially section 12)": "https://www.amazon.co.uk/Classical-Mechanics-Herbert-Goldstein/dp/8131758915"}
    },
    {
      "id": 9,
      "label": "Special Relativity",
      "color": "#dc3545",
      "description": "Starting with the idea that the speed of light is constant, Einstein developed a beautiful theory about how things move",
      "resources": {"The Theoretical Minimum: Special Relativity": "https://theoreticalminimum.com/courses/special-relativity-and-electrodynamics/2012/spring"}
    },
    {
      "id": 10,
      "label": "Classical Gauge Theory",
      "color": "#6c757d",
      "description": "It turns out our fundamental theories of nature are a described by a special kind of theory called gauge theories",
      "resources": {"Tong's Notes Ch 5": "https://www.damtp.cam.ac.uk/user/tong/em/electro.pdf", "Differential Geometry, Gauge Theories, and Gravity": "https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/differential-geometry-gauge-theories-and-gravity/2590331B00DB50D16192A96FFAFD1F8B","Geometry, Topology and Physics (Ch 1.8 and 10.5)": "https://www.amazon.co.uk/Geometry-Topology-Physics-Graduate-Student/dp/0750306068"}
    },
    {
      "id": 11,
      "label": "Quantum Field Theory",
      "color": "#20c997",
      "description": "Quantum mechanics meets special relativity and gives us our best theories for everything that isn't gravity",
      "resources": {"Quantum Field Theory": "https://www.amazon.co.uk/Quantum-Field-Theory-Mark-Srednicki/dp/0521864496"}
    },
    {
      "id": 12,
      "label": "Complex Analysis",
      "color": "#fd7e14",
      "description": "This is calculus but with complex numbers and it turns out to very useful for calculating integrals",
      "resources": {"Complex Analysis": "https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-1-4419-7288-0"}
    },
    {
      "id": 13,
      "label": "Lie Theory",
      "color": "#6610f2",
      "description": "In physics, we are often interested in continuous symmetries (like rotations) and this gives us the tools to study them.",
      "resources": {"Naive Lie Theory": "https://www.amazon.co.uk/Naive-Theory-Undergraduate-Texts-Mathematics/dp/0387782141", "Lie Groups, Lie Algebras and Representations": "https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-3-319-13467-3"}
    },
    {
      "id": 14,
      "label": "General Relativity",
      "color": "#e83e8c",
      "description": "Einstein's theory of gravitation which connects gravity and geometry",
      "resources": {"Spacetime and Geometry": "https://www.amazon.co.uk/Spacetime-Geometry-Introduction-General-Relativity/dp/0805387323", "General Relativity": "https://www.amazon.co.uk/General-Relativity-Robert-M-Wald/dp/0226870332"}
    },
    {
      "id": 15,
      "label": "Representation Theory",
      "color": "#e83e8c",
      "description": "This is all about how groups and matrices interact",
      "resources": {"Linear Representations of Finite Groups": "https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-1-4684-9458-7", "Ed Segal's Notes": "https://www.homepages.ucl.ac.uk/%7Eucaheps/papers/Group%20Representation%20theory%202014.pdf"}
    }
  ],
